<sn><md>## Mountain and Valley Breeze

![diagram](https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcT-RORVqE5wI6ni5TU0hGOy62FItXN-3yonLg&amp;s)

:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
#### Valley Breeze‚òÄ{.text-center}

* During the day, the **sun heats the mountain slopes** more quickly than the valley floor.
* The warm air on the slopes becomes **lighter and rises upward**.
* This rising air creates a **low-pressure area on the slopes**, and cooler air from the valley moves upward to replace it.
* This upslope movement of air is called the **Valley Breeze**.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
#### Mountain Breezeüåô {.text-center}

* At night, the **mountain slopes cool down quickly** compared to the valley floor.
* The cooler, denser air on the slopes **sinks downward** into the valley.
* This creates a **down-slope flow of air**, known as the **Mountain Breeze**.
::: 

:::


+++ Key Differences

| Aspect             | Valley Breeze (Day)              | Mountain Breeze (Night)      |
| ------------------ | -------------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| Time of occurrence | Daytime                          | Nighttime                    |
| Direction of flow  | From valley floor ‚Üí up slope     | From mountain slope ‚Üí valley |
| Cause              | Sun heats slopes, warm air rises | Slopes cool, cold air sinks  |
| Temperature of air | Warm, rising air                 | Cold, descending air         |
+++
</md></sn><sn><md>## What is Monsoon?

Monsoon is a ++seasonal reversal of winds++ that brings distinct `wet and dry seasons`, especially in tropical and subtropical regions. The word *monsoon* comes from the Arabic word *‚Äúmausim‚Äù*, meaning **season**.

:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
### Key Features of Monsoon{.text-center}

* **Seasonal Winds:** Winds change direction with the seasons.
* **Summer Monsoon:** Moist oceanic winds blow from sea to land, causing heavy rainfall.
* **Winter Monsoon:** Dry continental winds blow from land to sea, causing dry weather.
* **Driven by Heating Contrast:** Caused mainly by the ++differential heating of land and sea++ and the ++shifting of the Intertropical Convergence Zone (ITCZ)++.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
### Examples of Monsoon Regions{.text-center}

* **South Asia (India, Bangladesh, Nepal, Pakistan, Sri Lanka)**
* **Southeast Asia (Thailand, Myanmar, Vietnam, Philippines)**
* **Parts of Africa (West Africa, East Africa)**
* **Northern Australia**
:::

:::
</md></sn><sn><md>## Moonsoon

#### What is ITCZ?

The **Intertropical Convergence Zone (ITCZ)** is a **low-pressure belt** near the equator where the **northeast and southeast trade winds converge**. This zone is marked by rising warm, moist air, cloud formation, and heavy rainfall.

![diagram](https://www.insightsonindia.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/Indian-Monsoon2.jpg)

### How ITCZ Controls Monsoon

1. **Summer (Southwest Monsoon)**

   * During summer, the landmass (like India and South Asia) heats up strongly.
   * The ITCZ shifts **northward** (around 20‚Äì25¬∞N).
   * This attracts the **moist southwest monsoon winds** from the Indian Ocean toward the land.
   * Result: Heavy rainfall across tropical and subtropical Asia.

2. **Winter (Northeast Monsoon)**

   * In winter, the land cools down, and high pressure develops over the continent.
   * The ITCZ shifts **southward** back toward the equator.
   * Winds reverse direction and blow from land to sea (northeast monsoon).
   * Result: Dry weather over most of Asia, though southeast India and Sri Lanka get rain.

### Key Point

The **north-south shifting of the ITCZ** with the **apparent movement of the sun** is the **main driver of monsoon winds**.

| Season | ITCZ Position                   | Wind Direction                             | Effect                       |
| ------ | ------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------- |
| Summer | Shifts northward (20‚Äì25¬∞N)      | Moist winds from ocean ‚Üí land (SW Monsoon) | Heavy rainfall               |
| Winter | Shifts southward (near equator) | Dry winds from land ‚Üí ocean (NE Monsoon)   | Dry season (except SE India) |
